  "text": "_Results in Control and Optimization 14 (2024) 100401_ _G.R. Bhat et al._ **Fig. 2.** Autonomous Control Level (ACL) and trends of UAV autonomy [10]. temperature of the motors using heat sensors like DS18B20 [18]. In situations where the operating temperature of the motors rises above a particular threshold value, a landing process is initiated to ensure the safe landing of the drones to avoid further external damage. These sensors are mounted and interfaced with controller boards and the activity is tracked via a specially built user interface [19]. BLDC motors being the most essential in various applications have multiple control methods. However, the utilized hall effect sensors in BLDCs are not efficient enough, thus the back-EMF observer method is utilized for sensor less temperature control [20]. The benefit of using the back-EMF observer is that it determines the rotor position. A sensor-less rotor BLDC motor driver method using a back-EMF observer is presented in studies, this method is implemented for a 330 W motor with a 14.8 V rating [21]. Drones come into collision with environmental objects which occurs frequently due to failure in obstacle detection, territorial conditions, etc. To avoid collisions, a collision recovery algorithm is developed to control the recovery of the drone post-collision [22]. A novel design of a multilayer brushless DC motor specifically for UAVs and heavy payloads are introduced. The design focuses on enhancing torque at low speeds and optimizing motor performance through various winding configurations. This innovative solution holds promise for advancing the field of UAV propulsion systems [9]. Manufacturers aim to enhance the safety of drones, which has resulted in the utilization of propeller guards for protecting the propellers against external objects. However, propeller guards alone do not possess the capability to detect or counter collisions with obstacles such as walls and cables. To address this limitation, researchers have successfully developed and implemented a collision recovery solution as a safety feature in drone flight controllers. The integration of safety features at the motor level enables a drone to attain ACL of level 3 with certainty [23]. The outer rotor permanent magnet brushless DC motor for drones can be improved by incorporating a Halbach magnet array. Design optimization techniques are introduced to enhance its power characteristics and reduce weight. The goal of the manufacturers is to achieve improved performance compared to the currently used commercial drone motor [24]. ## **Flight control and ESC** The",
